The Stephen A. Era

Earlier this week, as I was hopping onto the subway, I texted my partner Jo=
hn Ourand to ask if he had any insight into Stephen A. Smith=E2=80=99s mont=
hs-long negotiation with ESPN. Back in the spring, as Puck devotees might r=
ecall, Stephen A. had made it clear that he wanted to become the network=E2=
=80=99s highest-compensated talent=E2=80=94perhaps turning his $12 million =
yearly deal into a $25 million annual payday.

Yes, it seemed like a strange moment in the history of cable television to =
ask for such a titanic raise, but Stephen A. had inarguably become ESPN=E2=
=80=99s most recognizable anchor, a celebrity worthy of those tacky tunnel =
cam videos, himself. It didn=E2=80=99t hurt, either, that Endeavor presiden=
t Mark Shapiro was personally working on the deal. WME, Endeavor=E2=80=99s =
talent representation business, had previously negotiated
historic packages for Joe Scarborough and Rachel Maddow, two other marquee =
earners in a declining industry. (Disclosure: WME represents Puck.)

My text to John was immediately prompted by a piece in The Athletic suggest=
ing that Stephen A. and ESPN were closing in on a $20 million-a-year packag=
e=E2=80=94not quite doubling his current salary but still nice work if you =
can get it. But I assumed that=E2=80=94as is often the case=E2=80=94the hea=
dline number was merely the tip of the iceberg, and wanted to know how the =
deal had come together: what Smith truly wanted, and what ESPN chairman Jim=
my Pitaro, a good guy in a business not exactly teeming with them, was will=
ing to concede.

The strategy behind the negotiation was intensely fascinating to me, I=E2=
=80=99ll admit. I came of age in the halcyon days of ESPN, when the =E2=80=
=9CThis Is SportsCenter=E2=80=9D ads had become cultural tropes and Stuart =
Scott=E2=80=99s most famous lines=E2=80=94cooler than the other side
of the pillow=E2=80=94were legit hallmarks. As I=E2=80=99ve noted before in=
 this space, the network was the profit center of The Walt Disney Company, =
and possibly the most important media entity in our economy.

And yet, things change. Just like CNN in the TV news space, ESPN has been b=
attered by the various headwinds reshaping media=E2=80=94a transformation d=
efined by rebundling, yes, but also the delicate choreography of managing t=
he decline of the cable business while growing a streaming enterprise=E2=80=
=A6 all while simultaneously servicing the needs of a large and historic pa=
rent company. Smith=E2=80=99s salary demand arrived just as Pitaro was cont=
emplating how he could optimize capital expenditure in the old world in ord=
er to propel ESPN=E2=80=99s forthcoming D.T.C. streaming property. This was=
 the story, I noted to John, that I thought he might probe.

Days later, a typical Ourand masterpiece arrived in my inbox. In Stephen A.=
 Backs Up the Brink=E2=80=99s Truck ( https://puck.news/stephen-a-smith-bac=
ks-up-the-brinks-truck/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F=
7%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F7%2F24%29&utm_m=
edium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a=
 ), John elegantly lays out the many backstage nuances of the deal=E2=80=94=
in particular, Pitaro=E2=80=99s recognition that Smith was, as they put it =
quite scientifically in Bristol, a needle-mover. Indeed, he was that rare b=
ird, along with Pat McAfee and a few others, who could command loyal rating=
s, justify ESPN=E2=80=99s price in the cable bundle, and facilitate the pat=
h to streaming. Amid this complex moment in our industry=E2=80=99s history,=
 Pitaro was simultaneously exiting replaceable stars and going all-in on mo=
re unique talents.

But perhaps the most relevant detail that John unearthed was that Smith=E2=
=80=99s deal was non-exclusive beyond sports. If Smith wanted to launch a S=
iriusXM
show about the culture, as has long been rumored, he=E2=80=99d have a green=
 light. =E2=80=9CThis type of concession would have been unimaginable just =
a few short years ago, in the Skipper era, when ESPN positioned itself as t=
he center of the sports media universe,=E2=80=9D John noted. =E2=80=9CAlas,=
 now all the large-platform companies getting into sports have prompted som=
e creativity.=E2=80=9D

