          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Earlier this week, =
as I was hopping onto the subway, I texted my partner <b>John Ourand </b>to=
 ask if he had any insight into <b>Stephen A. Smith</b>=E2=80=99s months-lo=
ng negotiation with ESPN. Back in the spring, as Puck devotees might recall=
, Stephen A. had made it clear that he wanted to become the network=E2=80=
=99s highest-compensated talent=E2=80=94perhaps turning his $12 million yea=
rly deal into a $25 million annual payday. <br/><br/>Yes, it seemed like a =
strange moment in the history of cable television to ask for such a titanic=
 raise, but Stephen A. had inarguably become ESPN=E2=80=99s most recognizab=
le anchor, a celebrity worthy of those tacky <i>tunnel cam </i>videos, hims=
elf. It didn=E2=80=99t hurt, either, that Endeavor president <b>Mark Shapir=
o </b>was personally working on the deal. WME, Endeavor=E2=80=99s talent re=
presentation business, had previously negotiated
historic packages for <b>Joe Scarborough </b>and <b>Rachel Maddow</b>, two =
other marquee earners in a declining industry. (Disclosure: WME represents =
Puck.)<br/><br/>My text to John was immediately prompted by a piece in The =
Athletic suggesting that Stephen A. and ESPN were closing in on a $20 milli=
on-a-year package=E2=80=94not quite doubling his current salary but still n=
ice work if you can get it. But I assumed that=E2=80=94as is often the case=
=E2=80=94the headline number was merely the tip of the iceberg, and wanted =
to know how the deal had come together: what Smith <i>truly </i>wanted, and=
 what ESPN chairman <b>Jimmy Pitaro</b>, a good guy in a business not exact=
ly teeming with them, was willing to concede.<br/><br/>The strategy behind =
the negotiation was intensely fascinating to me, I=E2=80=99ll admit. I came=
 of age in the halcyon days of ESPN, when the =E2=80=9CThis Is <i>SportsCen=
ter=E2=80=9D </i>ads had become cultural tropes and <b>Stuart Scott</b>=E2=
=80=99s most famous lines=E2=80=94<i>cooler than the other side
of the pillow</i>=E2=80=94were legit hallmarks. As I=E2=80=99ve noted befor=
e in this space, the network was the profit center of The Walt Disney Compa=
ny, and possibly the most important media entity in our economy. <br/><br/>=
And yet, things change. Just like CNN in the TV news space, ESPN has been b=
attered by the various headwinds reshaping media=E2=80=94a transformation d=
efined by rebundling, yes, but also the delicate choreography of managing t=
he decline of the cable business while growing a streaming enterprise=E2=80=
=A6 all while simultaneously servicing the needs of a large and historic pa=
rent company. Smith=E2=80=99s salary demand arrived just as Pitaro was cont=
emplating how he could optimize capital expenditure in the old world in ord=
er to propel ESPN=E2=80=99s forthcoming D.T.C. streaming property. This was=
 the story, I noted to John, that I thought he might probe.<br/><br/>Days l=
ater, a typical Ourand masterpiece arrived in my inbox. In <i><u><a href=3D=
"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUb1=
YzMUpSN2U1c3dCTmFVNlRXWT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3Mvc3RlcGhlbi1hL=
XNtaXRoLWJhY2tzLXVwLXRoZS1icmlua3MtdHJ1Y2svP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQmFja3N0=
b3J5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkY3JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGU=
rQmFja3N0b3J5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkY3JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxp=
bmtfaWQiOjIwMDg3Mjl9/ce8748723d3940a31256a7210dc99e7cd9232a591f3a77f95b6578=
a8355bda02" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" c=
lass=3D"sdf">Stephen A. Backs Up the Brink=E2=80=99s Truck</a></u></i>, Joh=
n elegantly lays out the many backstage nuances of the deal=E2=80=94in part=
icular, Pitaro=E2=80=99s recognition that Smith was, as they put it quite s=
cientifically in Bristol, a <i>needle-mover</i>. Indeed, he was that rare b=
ird, along with <b>Pat McAfee </b>and a few others, who could command loyal=
 ratings, justify ESPN=E2=80=99s price in the cable bundle, and facilitate =
the path to streaming. Amid this complex moment in our industry=E2=80=99s h=
istory, Pitaro was simultaneously exiting replaceable stars and going all-i=
n on more unique talents.<br/><br/>But perhaps the most relevant detail tha=
t John unearthed was that Smith=E2=80=99s deal was non-exclusive beyond spo=
rts. If Smith wanted to launch a SiriusXM
show about the culture, as has long been rumored, he=E2=80=99d have a green=
 light. =E2=80=9CThis type of concession would have been <i>unimaginable</i=
> just a few short years ago, in the <b>Skipper </b>era, when ESPN position=
ed itself as the center of the sports media universe,=E2=80=9D John noted. =
=E2=80=9CAlas, now all the large-platform companies getting into sports hav=
e prompted some creativity.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>I hung on to those words for =
a beat or two. We are in a new type of talent-driven economy, one where eli=
te creators are able to leverage the power of their platforms and their own=
 authentic voice. This is one of the great transformations in our time, and=
 the true leitmotif of Puck=E2=80=94a business built around our own needle-=
movers.<br/><br/>Have a great weekend,<br/>Jon<br/></td>
